        <mxCell id="p5-cmt-get" parent="1" style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;align=left;" value="&lt;font style=&quot;font-size: 14px;&quot;&gt;GET /video/{id}/comments: Check Redis cache first (fast). If miss → Query Cassandra with cursor-based pagination. Results cached back in Redis.&lt;/font&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="40" width="1100" x="40" y="790" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="p5-db-note" parent="1" style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;align=left;" value="&lt;font style=&quot;font-size: 15px;&quot;&gt;&lt;b style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Why Cassandra for Likes/Comments?&lt;/b&gt;  • Partition key = videoId → all data for a video on same node.  • High write throughput (likes can spike on viral videos).  • Linear scalability by adding nodes.  • Eventual consistency acceptable for social counts.&lt;/font&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="120" width="440" x="1060" y="110" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="p5-redis-note" parent="1" style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;align=left;" value="&lt;font style=&quot;font-size: 15px;&quot;&gt;&lt;b style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Why Redis for Counters?&lt;/b&gt;  • INCR is atomic → no race conditions.  • In-memory → microsecond latency.  • Prevents millions of DB writes on viral spikes.  • Periodic flush to Cassandra via Kafka consumer.&lt;/font&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="120" width="470" x="1060" y="290" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
